Journal from Elkton to the Mouth of Rogue River in the summer of 1859 by L.L. Williams; Elkton, the County seat of Umpqua County in the State of Oregon, is to be seen only as a preceived?, extending along the Umpqua River for the distance of about fifteen miles. A town has been surveyed off upon the west side of the Elk Creek, for the County seat, but as yet there are no public buildings, or buildings of any kind upon it Elkton derives its name from Elk Creek a stream of some 30 yds in width, which empties in to the Umpqua upon the North side, at a distance of fifty miles from its mouth and twenty from Scottsburg the head of navigation, also the head of Tide water upon said River Elk Creek derives its name from the numerous lands of Elk, that ranged upon its banks, and the open praries and unclear hills in its vicinity, previous to the valley being settled by the whites This part of the Umpqua Valley was settled about the year 1850, and for farming and grazing purposes, it cannot be surpassed by any other part of Southern Oregon. It is a rolling country, prarie and timber, with handsome River bottoms of farming, land not excelled by any other locality in Oregon

July 13th
Left Elkton for Scottsburg, twenty miles distant, where I arrived at 12 unclear The Road from Elkton to this place, passes through prarie Country and keeps in the immediate vicinity of the River. All the open land is claimed and occupied by farmers 

  As you reach within two miles of Scottsburg the Road enters heavy timber land, which continues to Scottsburg, the head of navigation upon the Umpqua River. 
  The timberd River Bottoms are generally covered with a thick growth of Myrtle, Maple with occasionally Alder, Ash & Willow, Cottonwood.
  Scottsburg is a dull place, consisting of one Store, Hotel and Black smith shope and nearly twenty empty buildings that are fast going to decay.
  In 1850 & 51 this place unclear fair to be the most flourishing town in Oregon, lots ranged high, buildings could scarcely be put up as fast as they were demanded by the traders who were every day arriving from the diferent parts of the Country to engage in business. At that time all the trade of Southern Oregon & Northern California unclear fair to be shipped to this post. But AD1833 a Road was opened through the Coast Mountains, from the mining country unclear a point on the Pacific that proved to be very much nearer than to this place, where a town was soon built up, and

aside from these rich bottom lands the open prarie country generally extends back to the hills, and forms what is termed "second bench land" which provides excellent grain but no as rich, or as good for garden vegetables as the River bottoms. And still further back are the high "Bato Hills"? which furnish to the agricultural community an excellent range for their stock. these hills are in places very much cut up with unclear and timbered gulches, and in many places may be found ledges and high cliffs of rock principally sand rock, which appears to be about the only formations (Geologcally)? in this vicinity, although in the gravel beds bordering the rivers, may be found pebbles of volcanic, slate & quartz, that have rolled on together into one common deposit

  The timber is principally fir, with quite an abundance of white & black Oak growing upon the borders of the unclear and upon the ridges. Cedar is found in the Canyons, and Laurel and a variety of small shrubbery in the Mountains 
  Game is abundant, such as Deer, Bear Geese, Ducks, Grouse, Pheasants, Pigeons Quails etc, Elk may be found quite plenty, within five or ten miles of the settlements, they confine themselves principally to the Mountains. Beaver and Otter and fish of various kind are found in the Rivers

Canons down which are numerous Cascade and waterfalls, roaring and leaping from rock to Crag, forming scenery, picturesque and beautiful in the extreme

  As the Boat reaches a point about five miles from the "Lower Town" the River is divided by a small low grassy Island into two Channels, the left Channel is only one used for navigation, and in this the water is shoal, not over one or two feet in depth at low tide. This shoal is called "Brandy Bar" and is the only obstruction to navigation from the Ocean to Scottsburg 
  At high tide there is from six, to ten? feet water on this bar, rendering safe navigation to River Streams of small Schooners. At this place the lands become less rocky, and you will notice a change in timber which is principally Spruce, growing upon low wet and swampy ground along the margin of the River
  At 18 miles from Scottsburg you pass the mouth of "Smiths River" a stream of about 100 yds in width, entering the Umpqua from the North, this River is navigable for River Steamers about 25 miles and for row boats some ten or twelve miles further to the head of tide water upon said stream
  There are a few settlers upon it, but not a country to even be very thickly populated 
  It runs through a high mountain Range

named Crescent City, from the Crescent shape of its harbor or Roads unclear upon which it is built, since the locality of this town, the most of the mining trade has been shipped there, consequently a nearly fatal blow to Scottsburg

  Scottsburg is named after its proprietor Capt Levi Scott, one of the pioneers of Oregon, who has gained the title of Capt during some of the early Indian wars

July 13th

  Took passage down River on board the Steamer "Sattelite", a pretty little Steamer for River or Bay navigations, and able to run at the rate of 15 miles per hour 
  One half mile below the town we passed a Sawmill upon the right bank. At the mouth of a rapid little Mountain stream of about 50 ft in width. And 1 1/2 miles farther passed what is denominated the "lower town", a place of 12 or 15 houses that were hastily put up when times were flourishing, in opposition to Scottsburg proper 
  These buildings are all vacated, and no business done here at all.
  The "lower town" or "Lower Scottsburg" is the terminus? of the River bottoms, and for about five miles farther the River is walled in with perpendicular walls and craggy escarpments of Sand Rock of two or three hundred feet in height cut up into chasms and deep narrow

Gardner, was also settled in 1850 and contains only one house

  About two miles below "Gardner" as the River turns to nearly a South Course, you have a fair view of Fort Umpqua and its adjacent buildings, situated in the drifting sand & just in the borders of a grove of spruce pine timber, a species of scrub pine, peculiar to a barren sandy soil
  After making the turn to the Southward the River runs paralel to the Coast (which is not over two or three miles off) for seven or eight miles forming a chain of drifting sand hills, interspersed with occasional groves and scattering spruce pine trees. These sand hills are composed of the white sand peculiar to the sea Coast, and are drifted in many places to the height of 100 feet
  Amongest this sand stands Fort Umpqua six miles from "Gardner" where we stopped for the night. At this place is an agency and Indian Reservation, upon which are collected the Umpqua & Coos Bay Indians numbering some two hundred, and are fed and cared for by the U.S. Government
  The opposite side of the River from the Fort consists of low mountains heavily timbered with Fir, Spruce, Hemlock Cedar 

July 14th

  The Boat got under way and after a run of six miles I was landed on the south side of

with only small narrow bottoms of land suitable for cultivation. In the mouth of Smith River is "Boldens Island" which appears to be a detached mountain of about 100 ft in height heavily timbered with fir, and about one half mile in length. The main Umpqua and the largest part of Smiths River passes to the left of the Island 

  Smiths River is named from Capt Smith an early Trapper and fur trader who crossed the continent via the Colorado River & explored the Coast from the Gulf of California to this place, where his company were all killed by the Indians except himself and one or two others, who at that time happened fortunately to be seperated from the balance
  After the loss of his company, he fled through the Mountains and joined the "N.W. Fur Company" on the Columbia River and was afterwards killed by the Indians somewhere in the New Mexican Country
  Passing the lower extremity of "Boldens Island" you have a fair view of Gardner City. The Port of Entry to the Umpqua River was settled in 1850 and as yet contains but one house and a Ware House & wharf
  At this place the River expands to about one mile in width with a few low marshy Islands near the south shore and a marshy border on the north
  The City of Providence is situated on the South side of the River opposite

while below high water mark it is hard & solid, so much so that horses leave unclear a print of their feet.

  Fortunately for me the Tide was in the ebb consequently first rate travelling 
  At ten miles from the mouth of Umpqua unclear a stream of some twenty feet in width breaking through the sand hills into the Ocean. This is called "ten mile creek", being equal distant from Umpqua & Coos Bay and the only fresh water between the two places
  It is also the County line between the two Counties of Umpqua & Coos 
  Passing this Stream about five or six miles, then bore off to the left, over the loose sand; about one mile to the beach of "Coos Bay", which like the Umpqua turns to the South at this place, running along paralel to the Coast from seven or eight miles to its mouth, thus forming a narrow range of low drifting Sand hills betwixt the Bay & Ocean 
  As I approached the Bay, "Empire City" the County Seat of Coos County loomed up magnificently upon the opposite side of the Bay & two or three miles farther down
  A pretty good quality of grass bordering the Bay, through which a good trail led down to the Ferry landing opposite the City. I hoisted the signal flag at the Ferry landing in accordance with

of the River about one half mile from its mouth. The River at the Bar, at low tide is about one fourth of a mile in width

  About 200 yds from the beach stands the Light House, a magnificent building erected during the Summer of 1857
  The Bar at the mouth of the River is a bad one, and many vessels were lost upon it during the first five or six years of the settlement of this part of the Coast 
  But of late, since the pilots have become better acquainted with the Channel and character of the winds and tide, the people of this place have not had occasion to record the loss of a single Vessel
  Here upon this Coast and among the Sand hills and along the River and Bays, may be seen the remains of the deserted Ranches of the Umpquas a once numerous Tribe from which the River takes it name 
  From this, my course was South along the beach, which is wholly composed of Sand, with drifting sand hills to your left, which extend from one to two miles back, and the raging billows continually tumbling and surging, to your right 
  By far the best travelling is when the tide is ebbing for the sand above high water mark, is generally of a drifting nature, causing very laborious travelling

large investments necessary to the construction of such buildings

  The shipping to this place is very limited, although there is a good entrance and a beautiful harbor the bay being about one mile in width. The County around about is not very mountainous, but very heavily timbered
  I was obliged to stop here for the night, not being able to reach the next settlement on the Coquille today
  July 15
      Left Empire City this morning the trail, led off directly from the Bay, into a heavily timbered Country, of Spruce, Hemlock Fir unclear with a thick undergrowth of Salmon Berry bush, which at this time were loaded with berries. The timber, particularly the Spruce, grows to a great height, of perhaps 250 or 300 ft, and from 8 to 10 ft in diameter
  About four miles from the Bay you enter forest that is composed wholly of dead timber, caused by fires which to all appearance, had raged fearfully at some late period. In this burnt land the trail was much obstructed by fallen timber, amongst which Blackberry Briers grew to such an extent, as to render the travelling almost anything but agreeable.
  About two and one half miles after you enter the burnt timber, you ascend

instructions which were posted in a conspicuous place, and had the satisfaction of seeing the Boat got under way, and in a short time I was landed on the opposite side in the suberbs of the City

  This Bay & vicinity was settled in 1853, during a great excitement, upon the discovery of extensive Coal beds in the neighborhood and rich placers of Gold on the beach; Empire City is the principal place, was (like thousands of other towns on this coast) built up in a hurry and died out as suddenly, it contains about twenty five houses, and not over five or six that are at present occupied, the remainder fast going to decay, in consequence of the Gold mines proving a failure and the Coal Banks not proving to be a paying institution
  The Coal mines are still worked to some little extent, but are yielding but little encouragement. Although Coal is abundant, yet its quality and the cost of labor, shipment unclear does not justify the proprietors of the "Beds" to drive the business very extensively
  A large Steam Saw Mill upon the upper border of the town, and another some few miles up the Bay, have been quite extensively engaged in the manufacture of lumber for the past two or three years but at the present time are motionless doing nothing, and apparently not paying a very heavy interest upon the

ascend a gentle rise which continues for about one fourth of a mile. when you arrive at the ruins of a deserted house, at one time during the first settlement of this part of the Coast was occupied by a family by the name of Yocum and in this family, on the 26th day of March 1855, there happened one of the most heart rendering calamities, that ever  befel any family upon this Coast. It was caused by a large spruce tree, of hug dimensions, falling upon the house, killing five little girls, daughter of Mr Yocum, the oldest fourteen years old and the youngest a child in its mother arms         It appears that the tree had been set on fire some time previous to the accident and several times during the day the family had left the house for safety, when just in the dusk of the evening, the tree fell with a terrible crash upon the house, hastening the five little innocents into eternity, while the brokenhearted parents, and two little boys were unclear to mourn over the mangled corpses of their Children and sisters. The two little boys were asleep in one extreme corner of the house and were uninjured, and what is much more strange, were not awakened until searches for as among the dead, Mr. Y. being outside the house discovered the unclear and gave the family warning, but alas was to late. The oldest girl, hearing her fathers warning, with a heroic courage rushed forward to save her little brothers
